column4: The information that was collected through resident interviews was incredibly enlightening and will inform many communications decisions in my office going forward. Our group lacks the resources to collect this type of information, so our messaging decisions and outreach efforts have often had to be based on case studies or best practices from other cities, or our best guess about the challenges facing typical Austinites. The insights gained from this research are just invaluable.
column11: Retrospective of Recycling Behaviors project with Austin Resource Recovery (May 2017)

column4: This was a very fun and exciting project, not to mention incredibly engaging and intriguing! I was so excited at every sprint review to see what was happening, what had changed, and the direction the project was headed. The final products are exactly what we need to move forward and supplement our strategy in the future to help move the needle on zero waste in our community. I wish this was an ongoing endeavor, because I crave more insights, but now the responsibility for seeing this incredible amount of research and product design through lays in our hands. And that is the most exciting part! The only feedback I have is in regards to media, especially television media. Some of the tv media cast a slight shadow on the department and could have used some PIO tweaking, if possible.

column4: I always looked forward to our meetings because they were interactive, fun, and I felt that my insights mattered. Also, I learned new nuances to recycling behaviors each time, which was really interesting. I liked the collaborative approach, and that these meetings offered me an opportunity to interact with others in my field, yet from different agencies. At first, this was one of the biggest draws to my interest in participating. It was a delightful deviation from the typical sit-n-listen meetings and really afforded participants the chance to interact in a way that not only helped the project (I hope!),  but that also strengthened our working relationships, which fosters cross-agency collaboration. I would add that while the remote participation is a good gesture, the nature of these meetings really requires in-person participation. I tried attending remotely once, and quickly realized that the value extends beyond the presentation - which is really the only part that can be digested while attending remotely. It is a tricky balance between wanting to be flexible for participants (and decreasing the need to add to Austin's traffic issues) and recognizing the magic that happens with face-to-face interaction.

column4: I think having a larger group could have been beneficial. Towards the end, I think we were all losing steam. And while I enjoyed the Sprint process and thought it was very interesting and thorough, I think it takes true dedication, of  which, I wasn't sure I truly felt. For future Sprints, it would be beneficial for participants to  be really invested in the subject/idea (and have the time) to make it more successful. I blame myself for not being as informed about the process as I should have been and feel my contributions weren't as valuable as I would have liked, but that isn't a fault to the organizer or the Innovation Office. I loved seeing the idea come together at the end and working with other departments and the participants from around the City. It was really cool to see an idea transformed into something tangible and I'd definitely recommend the process to others.

column4: Recommend in future:  Earlier notification and better overview of event plan for startup participants (e.g. I would have come into town earlier and participated in more of the mayor's events had we known about the overall schedule sooner), continue to fund some travel costs (without my getting plane ticket on miles we would have lost $$ on participating), provide clearer judging criteria to mayors and participants, provide access to more informal networking opportunities.  Better integration with the standalone smart city day events? Host a civic tech/ govtech/ mayors social event during the conference? (maybe there was one and we just weren't included?) Great components:  day pass to SXSW (perhaps get comp passes for each startup to festival?), stipend for participation, access to new potential markets, Austin city team was great and was very helpful.
